\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 Images in HTML Emails\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl330\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Images must be linked-to via an absolute address.
\b0\fs24 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\i\fs32 \cb3 Translation
\i0\fs24 : Images in your emails must be hosted somewhere on the Internet. They cannot be \'93attached\'94 to an email when you send it.\cb1 \

\b\fs32 \cb3 Images must always have a Title and Alt attribute.
\b0\fs24 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\i\fs32 \cb3 Translation
\i0\fs24 : Think about how many times you\'92ve opened an email to see a bunch of empty space and some plain text written with a prompt from your Email Client to \'93Show Images\'94 (or similar messaging).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl330\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 If you don\'92t include Alt and Title values for your images, your users may not see the information you want them to.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 CSS in HTML Emails\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl330\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 All CSS used in HTML emails must be inline. This means adding a style attribute to each and every tag you want to alter from its default state. You will also need to introduce some tags to add style to text components that otherwise are not referenced.\cb1 \
\cb3 Generally speaking, colors, height / width, border, padding, and typography (font, text-decoration, text-transform, line-height, etc.) are safe to use in HTML emails.\cb1 \
